---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Hampton Park has lots of older garages — are they harder to fit a new door to?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Slightly, but not a problem in practice. The 1980s–1990s Hampton Park brick veneer homes commonly have 2.1m ceiling heights and slightly out-of-square openings — we install with a low-headroom track kit (needs only 100mm headroom over the door) and fine-tune the door fit with adjustable side weatherseal. The result looks factory-fresh. Adds about $350–$500 to the standard install cost." }},
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Single garage or double — which is more common in Hampton Park?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "The older Hampton Park stock (1980s–early 2000s around Hallam Road, Coral Drive, Stuart Avenue) is roughly 70% single-garage, 30% double. The newer infill releases around Somerville Road are nearly all double-garage. Pricing scales accordingly — a single insulated sectional + opener installed is $1,800–$2,800, a double is $2,500–$4,800." }},
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Are tilt doors still worth repairing or should I replace?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Hampton Park has more original tilt doors than the newer Casey suburbs. Honest answer: if the springs are sound and the panel is straight, a tilt door is fine to repair for $200–$400. If the panel is bent, the bottom rail is rusted, or the door has been forced when off-track, you're better off replacing with a sectional. Sectionals are quieter, better insulated, more secure and lift vertically (so they don't swing out into the driveway like a tilt door does). Full sectional + opener replacement of an old tilt is $2,500–$4,000 for a single garage." }}
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Garage Doors Hampton Park | Install & Repair | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="Garage door installation, repair and motor replacement for Hampton Park — established 1980s–1990s homes plus newer infill. Tilt-to-sectional conversions, low-headroom installs, broken-spring same-day call-out."
  canonical="https://cranbournegaragedoorco.com.au/hampton-park/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Hampton Park &middot; established Casey suburb</span>
      <h1>Garage doors in <span class="accent">Hampton Park</span>.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        Hampton Park is older Casey &mdash; mostly 1980s&ndash;1990s brick veneer
        homes around Hallam Road, Coral Drive and Stuart Avenue, plus newer
        infill releases on Somerville Road. Older garages mean older doors:
        plenty of 25+ year-old tilt and side-hung timber doors due for
        replacement, and 1990s sectionals on their second motor.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Get a fixed quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Why Hampton Park</span>
      <h2>The Hampton Park garage door story.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>The tilt-to-sectional conversion is the big job here.</h3>
        <p>
          A lot of Hampton Park homes still have the original tilt door &mdash;
          you know the one, single rigid panel that swings up and out, takes
          your front bumper with it if you don&rsquo;t reverse far enough. The
          modern equivalent is a sectional door (lifts vertically in five
          horizontal panels, slides back along the ceiling). Sectional doors
          are quieter, better insulated, more secure, and don&rsquo;t arc out
          into the driveway. The conversion is straightforward &mdash; we
          remove the tilt mechanism, fit new tracks, install the sectional,
          fit a quiet belt-drive opener &mdash; usually a single day on site,
          $2,500&ndash;$4,000 for a single garage.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Low-headroom installs.</h3>
        <p>
          A lot of older Hampton Park garages have 2.1m ceilings (modern is
          2.4m). Standard sectional-door track kits need 300mm of headroom
          above the door, which often won&rsquo;t fit. We use a low-headroom
          track kit that only needs 100mm above &mdash; same door, same opener,
          just a different track configuration. Adds $350&ndash;$500 to the
          standard install.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Rust at the bottom rail.</h3>
        <p>
          The universal symptom of an old door in Hampton Park &mdash; rust at
          the bottom 100mm of the door panel where it meets the slab. The
          galvanised coating wears through, water pools after rain, the steel
          rusts out from the inside. Once rust is established, you can&rsquo;t
          repair it cost-effectively. Bottom panel replacement (on a sectional)
          is $550&ndash;$900 if the rest of the door is sound; if there are
          multiple problems we recommend full replacement.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">1990s opener replacement.</h3>
        <p>
          A lot of Hampton Park sectional doors are on their original 1995&ndash;2005
          opener &mdash; the loud screw-drive units with the green LED that
          flickers when a remote signal arrives. These are well past their
          12&ndash;18 year design life. The good news: keep the door, just
          swap the opener for a modern quiet belt-drive with smart-home support
          &mdash; $700&ndash;$1,400 fitted, transforms how the garage feels.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Typical Hampton Park jobs.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Tilt-door to sectional-door conversion on 1990s single garage ($2,500&ndash;$4,000)</li>
          <li>Low-headroom track-kit install in 2.1m ceiling garage ($350&ndash;$500 over standard)</li>
          <li>1990s opener swap for quiet belt-drive on existing door ($700&ndash;$1,400)</li>
          <li>Bottom-panel rust replacement on 20-year-old sectional ($550&ndash;$900)</li>
          <li>Spring + cable repair on Hampton Park sectional ($250&ndash;$550)</li>
          <li>Premium insulated double + smart Wi-Fi opener on Somerville Road infill ($3,500&ndash;$5,500)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Other service areas.</h2>
      <div class="areas-grid">
        <a class="area-pill" href="/cranbourne/">Cranbourne</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/berwick/">Berwick</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/narre-warren/">Narre Warren</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/endeavour-hills/">Endeavour Hills</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/city-of-casey/">All City of Casey</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <div class="cta-block">
        <h2>Same-day Hampton Park garage door call-out.</h2>
        <p>Tilt-to-sectional conversions, low-headroom installs, 1990s opener swaps &mdash; we know this suburb.</p>
        <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center;">
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
          <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Book online</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
